The cost effectiveness of influenza vaccination for adults aged 50 to 64 years: 
a model-based analysis for Spain.

Aballéa S(1), De Juanes JR, Barbieri M, Martin M, Chancellor J, Oyagüez I, 
Verwee B, Largeron N.

Author information:
(1)i3 Innovus, Uxbridge, UK. saballea@i3innovus.com

An economic evaluation of reducing the age threshold for routine influenza 
vaccination in Spain from 65 to 50 years was performed. A probabilistic model 
was used to compare a policy based on a recommendation to vaccinate all adults 
aged 50-64 with the existing vaccination policy for that age group, during 
interpandemic periods. Two perspectives were considered: third-party payer (TPP) 
and societal. Model inputs were obtained primarily from the published literature 
and validated through expert opinion. From TPP perspective, incremental 
cost-effectiveness ratios were estimated at euro14,919 per quality-adjusted 
life-year (QALY) gained and euro9731 per life-year gained. From societal 
perspective, the corresponding results were euro4149 per QALY and euro2706 per 
life-year gained. Extending routine influenza vaccination to people over 50 
years of age is likely to be cost-effective.

